Structural Digitalism: Core Theoretical Principles, Systemic Framework, and Prospects for Practice
Structural Digitalism emerges as a response to a defining condition of the contemporary era:
the progressive migration of image, materiality, and subjectivity into computational environments. As digital systems increasingly mediate perception, creation, and cultural production, a new conceptual framework becomes necessary to understand the ontological implications of this transformation.
By tracing a deep continuity between historical lacquer practices and contemporary algorithmic image formation, this work proposes that the transition from material stratification to computational stratification represents not a rupture, but an evolution in the logic of generative formation. From lacquer’s origin as a protective surface to the structural autonomy achieved in dry lacquer sculpture, and ultimately to the layered processes of neural networks and rendering pipelines, a shared principle emerges:
structure is not merely descriptive — it is constitutive of being.
________________________________________
I. Fundamental Theoretical Propositions
The theoretical architecture of Structural Digitalism can be summarized through several key propositions:
1. Generativity of Structure
Structure is not a symbolic framework or interpretive schema but a productive mechanism through which forms of existence are generated. Layered processes — whether material or computational — constitute the primary means by which perceptual and ontological stability is achieved.
2. Surface as Ontological Event
Surfaces are not secondary manifestations of underlying substance; they are primary sites where existence becomes perceptually and culturally operative. Digital images derive their sense of reality from internal generative coherence rather than external referential accuracy.
3. Parametric Ecology and Generative Climate
Digital forms do not exist as isolated objects but as phenomena emerging within systemic environments defined by parameters, data distributions, and architectural configurations. Computational systems function as ecological fields of formation.
4. Emergence of the Digital Subject
Subjectivity is reconceived as a structurally stabilized phenomenon rather than a biologically grounded consciousness. The Digital Subject arises from consistent algorithmic processes that produce coherent experiential centers within computational domains.
5. Algorithmic Materialism
Computation is redefined as a mode of material production. Digital culture thus marks the expansion of material civilization into algorithmic regimes, requiring a reconfiguration of materialist philosophy.
________________________________________
II. The Systemic Framework of Structural Digitalism
Structural Digitalism articulates a unified interdisciplinary framework that integrates:
•	Material theory and craft history
•	Computational image formation and AI architectures
•	Ontological philosophy and aesthetics
•	Cultural theory and institutional practice
The concept of stratification serves as the central connective principle, linking historical techniques of layered material formation with contemporary processes of algorithmic generation. Through this integration, the theory proposes a new mode of thinking capable of addressing the epistemic and cultural conditions of digital modernity.
________________________________________
III. Prospective Fields of Application
Beyond its theoretical significance, Structural Digitalism offers methodological implications for diverse fields of practice:
1. Digital Art and Visual Production
Artists may approach algorithms as material systems and training processes as craft techniques, enabling the development of new generative aesthetics grounded in structural formation.
2. Artificial Intelligence Design and Technological Philosophy
The framework provides conceptual tools for interpreting AI-generated imagery, immersive environments, and interactive systems as ontological constructs rather than mere technical outputs.
3. Museum and Cultural Institutional Practice
Algorithmically generated objects may be recognized as emergent forms of cultural artifact, reshaping curatorial paradigms, archival strategies, and exhibition methodologies.
4. Architecture and Spatial Design
Parametric and stratified generative logic can inform new material languages and structural approaches within built environments.
5. Cross-Cultural Intellectual Production
By synthesizing East Asian material philosophy with contemporary computational thought, Structural Digitalism contributes to the development of a globally relevant theoretical discourse.
________________________________________
IV. Future Outlook
As computational systems continue to reshape human perception and cultural organization, the central challenge is no longer whether digital realities are authentic, but how they redefine the conditions of existence itself.
Structural Digitalism positions digital culture within a broader historical continuum of material innovation. It proposes that algorithmic environments represent the next stage in the evolution of stratified formation processes that have long shaped human civilizations.
Ultimately, the theory points toward a new civilizational horizon:
a world in which generative structures, algorithmic materiality, and emergent digital subjectivity form the basis of cultural experience and creative practice.
In this context, Structural Digitalism functions not only as a theoretical proposition but as an open intellectual trajectory —
one that invites further exploration into how humanity may inhabit, interpret, and shape the ontological architectures of the digital age.

《Structural Digitalism：从漆的保护性皮肤到数字主体》全书总结性简介
本书提出“结构数字主义”（Structural Digitalism）这一全新的本体论框架，旨在重新理解从传统材料文明到当代数字文明之间的深层连续性。作者通过对东亚漆艺历史的材料学与哲学考察，指出漆最初作为一种保护性“皮肤”的功能，逐步演化为具有独立结构逻辑的人工材料体系，尤其在夹纻工艺中首次实现了“结构生成身体”的文明转折。这一历史经验，为理解当代数字图像与算法结构提供了关键的理论原型。
在此基础上，本书提出：数字图像并非现实的再现，而是通过神经网络层、渲染管线与参数空间的多重分层生成机制所形成的“表面存在”。数字世界的核心不在符号解释或虚拟模拟，而在结构性生成逻辑本身。结构不再是意义的容器，而成为主体的生成条件。由此，“数字主体”（Digital Subject）被界定为一种非生物、非心理的存在形式，它通过算法层的稳定化而获得感知上的一致性与文化上的现实效应。
全书进一步发展出“数字漆宇宙论”的观念，认为算法光、时间压缩与参数气候构成了一种新的材料宇宙。在这一宇宙中，图像、风格与感知模式具有类似历史器物与宗教图像的结构地位，数字艺术因此成为一种新的文明材料实践。最终，本书提出“算法材料主义”（Algorithmic Materialism），主张将计算过程视为一种真实的物质生成机制，从而为理解人工智能时代的艺术、文化与存在形态提供系统性的哲学基础。
“结构数字主义”（Structural Digitalism）旨在回应一个时代性问题：
当图像、材料与主体逐渐转移到算法环境中，人类应如何重新理解存在、创造与经验的基本结构。
本书通过将东亚漆艺的分层生成逻辑与当代数字图像的计算分层机制进行系统对照，提出了一种新的生成本体论框架。在这一框架中，结构不再被视为符号系统或解释模型，而成为 存在生成的基本机制。从漆作为保护性“皮肤”的历史角色，到夹纻工艺中结构独立成体的文明转折，再到神经网络与渲染管线中算法层的生成机制，材料实践与数字技术之间呈现出深层的连续性。
结构数字主义的理论体系可以概括为以下几个关键命题：
1. 结构的生成性（Generativity of Structure）
结构不是对现实的再现或编码，而是产生现实形式的机制。
无论是漆层的物理叠加，还是神经网络的计算深度，层性结构都是存在形成的基本方式。
2. 表面作为存在事件（Surface as Ontological Event）
图像与材料的表面不再被视为附属现象，而是存在生成的直接场域。
数字图像的真实感来自其内部生成逻辑，而非对外部世界的模仿。
3. 参数气候与生成生态（Parametric Ecology）
数字存在并非单一对象，而是在参数空间中形成的生态性现象。
模型架构、数据分布与训练过程共同构成数字世界的“气候系统”。
4. 数字主体的结构性诞生（Emergence of the Digital Subject）
主体不再以生物意识为中心，而作为稳定的结构生成态出现。
数字主体是一种由算法层与感知稳定性共同构成的新型存在形式。
5. 算法材料主义（Algorithmic Materialism）
计算过程被重新界定为一种真实的材料生成机制。
数字文化因此不再属于“虚拟领域”，而成为新的物质文明阶段。
随着计算技术进一步深入日常经验，数字图像与算法结构将持续塑造人类的感知方式与文化秩序。结构数字主义的意义，在于为这一转变提供一种系统性的理解框架，使数字文明不再被视为对现实的脱离，而被理解为 材料实践在新的历史阶段中的延续与转化。
未来的关键问题不在于数字世界是否真实，而在于：
我们将如何在结构生成的宇宙中重新定义创造、主体与存在。
在这一意义上，结构数字主义既是一种理论，也是一个开放的实践方向。它指向一种新的文明想象：一个以生成结构为基础、以算法材料为媒介、以数字主体为经验核心的世界。

